import java.io.*;
import org.jsoup.*;
import org.jsoup.nodes.*;
import org.jsoup.select.*;

public class HtmlParser {

    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {
        // Load the HTML content from a file
        File input = new File("index.html");
        Document doc = Jsoup.parse(input, "UTF-8", "");

        // Extract the necessary information using selectors
        Elements titles = doc.select("h2.title");
        Elements contents = doc.select("div.content");

        // Create a hashmap to store the extracted information
        HashMap<String, String> resultMap = new HashMap<String, String>();

        // Loop through each element and add it to the hashmap
        for (int i = 0; i < titles.size(); i++) {
            String title = titles.get(i).text();
            String content = contents.get(i).text();
            resultMap.put(title, content);
        }

        // Output the hashmap for debugging and validation purposes
        System.out.println(resultMap.toString());
    }
}
```

In the code above, we use the JSoup library to parse the HTML content stored in a file named "index.html". We then use CSS selectors to extract two types of elements from the HTML structure: `<h2>` tags with a class of "title", and `<div>` tags with a class of "content".

We then create a hashmap and loop through each element we extracted, adding its text content to the hashmap using the title as the key and the content as the value.

Finally, we output the contents of the hashmap for debugging and validation purposes.

Note: To use JSoup in your Java project, you will need to include the JSoup JAR file in your classpath. You can download the latest version of JSoup from the official website: https://jsoup.org/download.

